items.title: Curiosity
items.body: This is probably OT but I was wondering... how did you manage to implement (and I suppose test) uptime on so many different platforms? =)

items.title: -b ends with traceback
items.body:
At the moment I'm packaging uptime for Fedora and Alpine Linux. While running uptime on both I get trackbacks.

``` bash
alpine00:~$ python -m uptime
Uptime: 5 days, 23 hours, 9 minutes, 51.42 seconds.
```

but -b gives the traceback

```
alpine00:~$ python -m uptime -b
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/runpy.py", line 162, in _run_module_as_main
    "__main__", fname, loader, pkg_name)
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/runpy.py", line 72, in _run_code
    exec code in run_globals
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/uptime/__main__.py", line 41, in <module>
    sys.stdout.write(time.strftime('Booted: %c.\n', boot))
TypeError: argument must be 9-item sequence, not datetime.datetime
```

The installed Python version

```
alpine00:~$ python
Python 2.7.5 (default, Sep  1 2013, 04:25:16) 
[GCC 4.8.1] on linux2
Type "help", "copyright", "credits" or "license" for more information.
>>> 
```

With Python3 I get:

```
$ python3 -m uptime -b
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "/usr/lib64/python3.3/runpy.py", line 160, in _run_module_as_main
    "__main__", fname, loader, pkg_name)
  File "/usr/lib64/python3.3/runpy.py", line 73, in _run_code
    exec(code, run_globals)
  File "/usr/lib64/python3.3/site-packages/uptime/__main__.py", line 41, in <module>
    sys.stdout.write(time.strftime('Booted: %c.\n', boot))
TypeError: Tuple or struct_time argument required
```
